  "opinion": "Stereotype threat in STEM isn't something I've ever really encountered myself, but I've seen it play out in my own life and the lives of my neighbors. Growing up in a small town in Italy, my parents both had limited education, and I was never pushed to go into science or engineering. I worked as a mechanic for 30 years, and I've met many people who struggle with the same thing: the fear that they're not 'good enough' in fields where they're not traditionally represented. For example, when I'm at the workshop and a young person comes in asking about how to fix a car, they often say they're not 'smart enough' to handle it, and that's because they've been told they don't belong in technical fields. This isn't just about individual confidence—it's about a cultural belief that certain people can't succeed in STEM. I think we should address it, but not in a way that's too academic or theoretical. We need to start with the basics: teaching people that everyone has the ability to learn technical skills, no matter their background. In my shop, I've seen it work when I take time to explain things simply and without judgment. If we can create an environment where people feel safe to make mistakes and ask questions, then we can help break down these stereotypes. It's not about changing the system overnight—it's about small, consistent steps that build confidence and show that anyone can learn. I've noticed that when people feel supported, they often surprise themselves with what they can do.",
